fields.summary: Comments will go here

Despite a great turn out and three runners in the top ten (Josh 2nd, Dave 9th and James 10th) the senior men are still stranded in fourth spot. It seems the poor scoring in the first race of the season will be just too much to claw back. The vets continue to show great form but have slipped a place to fourth but are certainly in a position to medal on the last race. There were only two finishers in the womenâ€™s race and they are now down to seventh. The goal will be to avo.

Elsewhere the U13 boys have resolutely hung on to silver position by a slender margin but the girls have slipped a few places to 10th. They finish in those positions since this age group is being scored on three races only. The U15 girls just retain third spot and the U15 boys are up to fifth with another winning run by Charlie Grice. No under 17 girls team but the boys have moved up another place to fourth.

Paul Thomas, AWAD (Athletes with a Disability) Phoenix member, running with the a, managed to do 6km (3 laps) which is further than he has ever run before. Congratulations to him.
Sophie Coleman came 6th junior women. Charlie Grice 16th U15. Liz Durman 137th senior women. Pat Davoren 166th senior men. Malcolm Hughes 800th, Ian Moss 1101th.

Stand out performances by Dave Carter (4th in 1:13:07) and James Miles (8th in 1:15:57) gave the senior men second team spot with Tom Naylor (35th in 1:20:32) and Mike Murphy (43rd in 1:21:16) completing the A team line-up. Age category awards Andy Field (1st M60 1:28:46, Bob Novis (3rd M50-59 1:23:42). In the womens race Erica Martin ran a fine 1:25:37 for 8th place with Sharon Young (57th 1:36:28), Anita Jones (68th 1:37:39) and Carolyn Austin (968th 2:11:24) taking the ninth team spot out of 60 completing. 30 Phoenix athletes competed in total.

With some of our senior men absent it was always going to be a big ask to get into the medals at this final league race given their disastrous race 1 turnout. Amazingly with Dave carter  (6th), Matt Barrie (7th) and Dan Stepney (15th) leading the way we managed the bronze medal. The vets performed well as ever but finished (just) in fourth spot.

The senior women had another poor turnout and although Erica Martin excelled for fifth they languish 7th out of eight first division teams and are in danger of relegation to division 2 next season.

Elsewhere Charlie Grice completed a fantastic season with another win to become indiv.  Under 17 boys came fourth overall with good seasons By Finn MacNally and Max Pickard. Under 15 girls were 4th and there was no under 17 team. Under 13 results were declared after three matches and the under 13 boys were top Phoenix team making silver.

There was Phoenix representation across the board in Sussex vests for the Inter-county championships. Star of the day was Charlie Grice who was 6th in the U15 boys. Sophie Coleman suffered cramp problems in the early part of her race and will be disappointed with her, otherwise impressive, 10th spot in the under 20 women’s race. She was hoping for a top 5 position to cement her claim for a GB place in the World Championships.

Other Phoenix placings: James Miles 256th SM, Finn MacNally 114th U17B, Robbie Fitzgibbon 46th and Billy White 64th U13B, Liz Durman 209th SW, Beth K103rd and Megan K 263rd U15G.

Isn't life surprising. We've been commenting lately about relatively few women competing in running events and then bingo! – an unheard of four teams are entered for this event. What's more we've shown what we can do – with the A team (Erica Martin, Sundai Boulton and Liz Durman) winning a neck and neck battle with Horsham Blue Star for first spot. The B team(Angel Collins, Rachel Phelps, Erica Martin) would have placed seventh but for Erica running a second leg. As it was the C team (Deb Friis, Faye McClelland, Liz Hall) were placed 9th and the D team (Hildi Mitchell, Sue Hudson and Ananda Mello-Costa) placing 13th.

The senior men also triumphed with Dave Carter, Charlie Grice, James Miles and Finn McNally running themselves into second place.

Elsewhere Archie Davis and Billie White ran great legs in the U13 boys event but lacked a third runner for what might have been a winning team. The U15 boys (Luke Reynolds, Jack Donaghy and Robbie Fitgibbon) were 4th team. Paul Collicutt and Malcolm Hughes ran well for the masters but alas were two runners short.

Great weather, great organisation, great support. The inaugural Brighton Marathon was a success beyond most people's expectation. And Phoenix featured large on the day. Second claim member, Tom Naylor was, with Tim Hutchins, the event organiser – so hearty congratulations to them. Olympic Champion and club founder Steve Ovett started the race. Mike Whyte and Tim Woodman fulfilled their pacing roles to perfection and, of course, 29 of you took part and came up with some quality performances. We had four runners under three hours led by returning member Neil Boniface (7th in 2:41:23). Mike Greenwood ran the best judged race of all finishing 18th in a time of 2:50:13 which shaves his previous best by some 25 minutes!. Good to see Daryl Hards back in shape and although he slipped back in the closing miles managed an impressive 2:54:36. Max-Patrick Lippert was supposed to be running the Boston Marathon but his plans fell to ash (of the Icelandic variety) but he was offered a last minute place in the race and responded with an even-paced 2:59:42 for 90th position. As you can see from the list here, a further 18 Phoenix athletes finished under four hours with everyone safely home by five. As if that weren't enough, Charlie Grice won the mini mile event. Last year Charlie broke Steve Ovett's 800m Brighton schoolboy record, taking it down to 1:55.80. On Sunday he got to meet the great man in person. Archie Davis was first U13 boy in the mini mile.

And they're off! Cross-country league 1 took place at Goodwood on Saturday 23 October. The good news is that Phoenix were represented in all age groups, both male and female. The less good news is that The U17 boys, the U15 girls, the U13 girls and the senior women were short of a full scoring team. The points are made up by taking the number of runners in each race and adding ten points to complete the scoring and that is a heavy penalty!

The U13 boys are in a handy 6th place, within striking distance of the medals. Archie Davis ran an excellent race for 4th with the ever reliant Matt Berr and Will Russell backing him up. The U13 girls are in 11th place with Charlotte Matthews and Madeline Houghton running sol.

In the U15 categories Jody Mann was only representative for the girls, running well for 12th. The U15 boys with four runners led by Billy White (3rd) were second team.

In the U17 boys event Charlie Grice cruised to a well-judged win with Will Durkin impressing for 5th place. They are 5th as a team.

The senior women would have scored well with a third runner to back up Liz Durman (12th) and Deb Friis (59th). As it happened the cavalry in the guise of Anita and Rachel arrived just too late for the start. So – they are languishing in division 2 for the moment.

The senior men were short of a few lead runners for one reason or another but put in a spirited performance with Finn McNally (6th), Max Pickard (7th), new member Tom Hopkins (9th) and James Miles (16th) putting us into an excellent 2nd position.

The vets led by Garry Thayre (51st) are in 5th but just a handfull of points away from 3rd spot.

Three to go and all to play for as they say, but let's complete those teams folks.

It's the boys teams that are still keeping the Phoenix flag flying. The U13 boys fielded 5 runners with Archie Davis (3rd), Reuben Hoyte (4th), Isaac Wright (9th) running exceptionally well, with Joe Lillie and Will Russell in support. Winners on the day, the team have now moved into bronze position overall. The U15 boys have jumped from 7th to 4th overall with excellent runs from Billy White (3rd), Sam Kitchen (14th) and Luke Reynolds (21st). Thats where it stops with the under 17 boys without a team and no longer featuring in the tables.

Well done to Charlotte Matthews, Elorah Mann (U13G), Jodie Mann, Amber Muir (U15G) for strong performances. Its always going to be difficult to trouble the medals without full scoring teams. The U15s, though, have moved up from 9th to 8th place.

Then – oh dear – the senior turnout was dire. The women first. TheU17 runner Megan Lillie, was the ONLY Phoenix runner. She ran brilliantly for 30th place but in division 2, the women's team has now plunged from third to fifth position overall.

The men too were unable to provJames Miles (an excellent 9th) the only senior runner. As ever it was down to the four vets who turned up to prov. Bruce Warren (33rd), Nigel Herron (48th) and Malcolm Hughes (69th) ran well, with O65 runner Andrew Haig (91st) unexpectedly having to contribute to the scoring. Inevitably the seniors have slipped from third to 4th overall but with 34 points separating them from bronze could still get among the medals at Lancing. The vets have slipped a place to 5th but it's very tight with just 11 points separating them from bronze-placed Arena 80.

THIS FROM U13 BOYS MANAGER QUENTON DAVIS:
…the U13 Boys now lie in bronze position in the team event overall. Statistically, we have not yet fielded our strongest 3 runners in any of the first 3 matches. Brighton & Hove have pretty much run away with the gold medal  but Chichester, currently in 2nd place,  are now only 15 points ahead of the Phoenix Boys. After the great performances on Saturday at Bexhill, we took the team event over Chichester by 12 points. With Archie Davis now looking like he is back to full fitness and the other boys all improving with every match, particularly Reuben, Matt Berr, if we manage to field our strongest teams at Lancing, it may all get very interesting indeed. Whatever the outcome, this has been an outstanding cross country season for the Phoenix U13 Boys, who are pretty much all in their first season and with the exception of Will Russell, all eligible to compete in this age group again.

At the last cross-country league race at Lancing on the 12th February, the Under 13 boys team who have been excellent all season took first place on the day and claimed silver team medal for the season.

With seven athletes in the team all performing well, the lads really showed the rest of us how its done. Team manager Quenton Davis puts it this way: 'I think a combination of up-and-coming talent & and our commitment to attendance in numbers saw us through'

Archie Davis was first home in third place just 23 seconds off the lead. Archie was unlucky to miss out on the indiv. Then we had Matt Berr 7th, Reuben Hoyte 9th, Isaac Wright 12th, Will Russell 32nd and Josh White 40th. Joe Lillie was unlucky to have to withdraw with an injury.

U15 boys featured two ever-reliable athletes Sam Kitchen 9th and Luke Reynolds 21st and place sixth for the year.

There was no U17 boys team featuring at all in the results.

Charlotte Matthews ran well again for the U13s but without support the team was just 11th for the season. Jody Mann 6th, and Amber Muir 14th ran well for the under 15 girls but without a full team had to settle for 6th overall.

The senior women fielded just two runners, Liz Durman 15th and Megan Lillie (U17) 42nd. After poor representation all season they languish 5th in the second division.

The senior men again featured just two runners (James Miles an excellent 9th and Andrew Neighbour 69th) and had to depend on the vets for their scoring including 60+ runner Malcolm Kemp. They were inevitably well short of the medals in 5th place. The vet men have been reasonably represented during the season but were without their strongest team at Lancing. They held on to fifth place. Nigel Herron ran a terrific 34th and Malcolm Hughes 55th and Lance Bellers 67th were the other scorers.

We need to dec, if so, what can we learn from the U13 boys team?

The inaugural running of the Phoenix 10K was an undoubted success. Not only d. With chip-timing and well -organised facilities such as toilet provision, baggage tent, massage, PA (great work Tim) etc, the oveall impression was highly favourable and bodes well for the future.

Congratulations have to go to Andy Bone who has steered the event with consumate organisational skill. The marshalling and bike-leading too was excellent with Liz Hall, Eleanor Moore, Malcolm Kemp and others assuming responsibility. Particularly heartening was the raucus reception committee of junior athletes, organised by John Marinko, at the 5K turnaround point.

It also turned out to be a high quality race with a sprint to the finish with Dean Lacey of Cambr's Ian Leitch by three seconds. Josh Guilmant of Phoenix was just 30 seconds back in third place. Phoenix won the men's team prize (Leitch, Guilmant, Hopkins, Hards). A special mention too for Terry Avey who's running has transformed this season. He was first in the over-60 category against a qualty field in that age-group, with a superb sub-40 run. Amazingly, this is his eighteenth age-group first this season.

In the women's race Emma Richards of Hailsham Harriers was run away winner in 37:35, a substantial PB for her. The next two places were fought out by two V45 athletes. Elspeth Turner of Horsham Blue Stars was second in 38:17 and Cathy Ulliot of Brighton and Hove was third in 40:13.

Thirty-one of us competed and here are our results (chip times). Well done everybody.

At a sunny but windy Goodwood, where dry conditions meant flats were more prevalent than spikes, Phoenix athletes had a successful day at the first Sussex x-country league race, with four indiv, Mathew Berr. There was one second, Archie Davies U13 boys and two thirds, Jake Elliot 17 Boys and Erica Martin Senior/Vet Women.  Special mentions to Max, who although U20 won the senior men’s race, which had its largest field for some time, also to Erica, who in her own words had her best x-country race for some time and although third overall was first senior women.

The league is not just about indiv, every place matters. It was therefore pleasing to see that the fine indiv, with team victories in the U13 and U17 boys. A more detailed report for the U13 boys can be seen below, unfortunately Isaac Wright suffered an injury in the U13 race and we wish him a speedy recovery. It was good to see complete teams in the U13 girls and senior women, who in the past have struggled to make teams.  It was noted that it was up to Max and the ‘older’ men to make up the numbers in the senior men’s team, with Donald Maclellan running his first x-country race for Phoenix leading the Phoenix vets home. Donald also won the post race cake eating prize!

Well done to all those who attended, the next league races are on November 26th at Plumpton.

U13 boys report by Quenton Davis - We went into the first league match conf, even with the absence of Reuben Hoyte from that gold medal winning team. With six boys available on the day we were also conf. Matt Berr, a tactic that saw them steadily work clear of Lewes in third place. By the last 200m the two Phoenix boys were well clear and the inform Matt Berr.
Ollie Johnson came home in 15th place in his ma. The B team were looking good for a m, Joe Lillee and Harry Swindells but unfortunately Isaac sustained what appears to be a pretty serious knee injury in the last third of the race. At twelve years old and a talented competition cyclist this could very likely end Isaac's cross country season; we all wish him a speedy recovery. The B team still managed a fantastic 12th position and hopefully with the three or four good runners we still have to call on we can push the B team up the table over the last three matches

His winning time of 15:06 smashed the course record by an incredible 31 seconds and was an incredible 93 seconds ahead of the next placed athlete. Superb running Josh. These facebook comments are an indication of how awed people were:

Mark Ryalls I still can't believe the guy that won it, like Billy Whizzz!

TL Sports Events He was amazing, such smooth graceful running, he was definitely in a . And such a lovely, down to earth guy to chat to. Fantastic to see the course record smashed!

Capitan Slow He asked me a bout the course before the race and I told him all about it, I even mentioned "don't worry you won't get lost, just follow the crowd " !! as if....

Terry Avey was the only other Phoenix runner and he recorded a staunch 20:17 for 2nd M60

Some fantastic competing was seen at the Phoenix Open Track Meeting at Withdean Stadium, May 8th. Athletes of all ages competed in events from 100 metres, 800 metres, 1500 metres, 3 km and steeplechase runs to standing long jump and long jump.

Phoenix was out in force with record numbers of runners in the junior races.
In the closed 100m Sophia Warner narrowly missed the qualifying time for the World Para Athletics Championships with what was still a great run.
In the very competitive 800 metre BMCA race Matt Favers showed great ability to accelerate at pace in the last 50 metres to win.

Yet further success, in the form of personal bests, was seen for Billy White in the A race and Spencer Thomas looking good to win the B. And there was yet another outstanding front run by Almi Nerurkar in the under 13 girls 800 metres.

Tom Hopkins and Richard Moult from Phoenix tuck on the Ghurkha Trailwalk UK Challenge along with Tom's wife Sarah and close friend Barbora. Regardless, the whole team finished with the help of their dedicated support crew in a respectable 26hours 9mins. It's a truly amazing event and well worth a go!

There are people who love this sort of thing. There are people in Phoenix who love this sort of thing! It was wet, it was off-road and it was muddy. Not only that it was over distance – 28.2 miles. Essentially an out and back along the river Adur, the route takes a detour to the epomymous Dark Star Brewery at the turn around but I don't think a compensatory pint was on offer. The race was restricted to 60 entrants and our gallant team all made it into the top half.

The race was won in 3:46:38. Tom Fars ran 4:10:24 for an impressive third. Andy Pumphry ran 5:18:17 for 24th and Brian Friend 5:24:05 for 29th.

Part 3 of the league saw some more fine performances, and another good turnout despite the wind.  It was great to see some new faces joining in with the fun.

Notable results include Milly Dickinson's 2nd place (U13 girls), Almi Nerurkar's 3rd (U15 girls), Elishka Coupar's 2nd (U17 women), Ollie Jonhson's win (U17 men) and Dave Carter's 3rd (O40 men).  All of these are in a good position to win a medal after the final race in February.

Team standings are also looking very healthy, with most teams climbing up the rankings, in some cases with two teams in the top ten in a given .  This goes to show the importance of consistent turn out.  With a strong showing in the final race, the U13 girls, U13 boys, U15 girls, U17 men, and O40 men should all be challenging for team medals, and the senior women should seal a win in their division.

The South Downs Way Relay is so popular that Phoenix was reduced to three teams this year from our usual four, to make room for newcomers. The race is limited to sixty teams of six, each with a support van and driver/navigator. The 100 miles from Eastbourne to Winchester is div.

The Phoenix A team (Donald Maclellan, Jose Muzio, Jim Whitelegg, James Miles, Alex Bonzi, Mark Cossey and driver/navigator Louise Gregory) suffered bad luck on the first leg with James injuring his ankle and unable to continue. Out of the race as such, they voted to carry on with their allotted legs but with the pressure off "running free". This proved to be a wise choice allowing Jose to break the club senior record for leg 5 and Donald to break the vet's records for legs 6 and 18!

The Phoenix B team (Pete Goodman, Jon Wright, Malcolm Kemp, Richard Thompson, Andrew Neighbour, Anita Jones and driver/navigator Sue Hudson) ended the day as silver medalists in that category, running 11:38.52 just 10 minutes behind the leaders.

The Phoenix women's team (Erica Martin, Bobby Searle, Liz Hall, Hannah Carey, Kath Harnett, Caz Garrett with driver navigator Hildi Mitchell) were seventh out of 10 in their category in a respectable 13:33.55.

Well done everybody

A link to detailed results will appear as soon as they are available.

The Putbosstadion Vlierzele, Oordegem in Belgium, saw the lads from Brighton Phoenix all recording new PB’s in impressive .

Robbie Fitzgibbon, who was fresh from a 5-week training stint in Flagstaff, Arizona with Mo Farah, Matt Centrowitz and Charlie Grice, became only the 25th U23 to dip under 3:40 for the 1500m. He was placed third in race two. This gives him the qualifying time for the U23 European Champs in Poland in a few weeks time and extra determination to qualify for the European Senior Championships in Amsterdam.

Archie Davis had posted another 1500m PB (3:45.43) in race 1, to move ever closer to the standard for the same Championships in Bydgoszcz, Poland.

Spencer Thomas was 1st in the 8oom 'After Programme' securing his long awaited World Junior Championships qualifying time with 1:48.24.

Sensational running guys.

All three runners will have the chance to improve their case for selection in a series of fast races later this month.

"Not a race": Reliability Trials are, like Audax events, not races, but rather long distance r, self reliance and navigational skills.

How Reliable a cyclist are you?

  • Fitness - Do you think you are fit enough to complete the course in your sellected time?
  • Self Reliance - Are your skills, equipment & machine reliable enough to deal with any mechanical or climatic conditions which could occur on the day?
  • Navigational Skills - Can you successfully navigate the course, passing through all the required controls using the directions prov?

    The proof of a reliable cyclist, in the spirit of Reliability Trials is someone who can answer yes to the above 3 questions!

    A reliable cyclist is not someone who trains numerous times before the event on a pre-published route. Neither is it someone who follows their handlebar mounted satellite navigation system around a way-marked route on the day of the event (there are plenty of sportives throughout the year for cyclists who want to do that).

    Our Phoenix cyclists had to r, finisihing within 2:50-3:10 hours.  Jon Wright was spot-on with 3h, Jim Whitelegg a safe 2:59, and Andy Bone came in at 2:52 - but d?

    Phoenix Team came 5th overall.

This popular seasonal race is not as easy as it might sound. Six miles of it are off road and there is a challenging hill at the six mile mark. Oh, and it were darnn cold on them thar hills.

Terrific performances then by our three runners.

Darryl Hards won the event in a blistering 57.54, well over a minute ahead of the second placed runner.

Georgia Flowers was 84th in a time of 1:19.15

Kim Hards was 4th M60, 142nd in 1:25.50

Well done all

And, in a race with over 12000 finishers, four runners in the top 100 is good going. Well done all.

A very popular event in the club calendar.  The race covers the whole of the South Downs Way, from Beachy Head to Winchester.  Teams of six take on the 100 miles, which is div.

This year Phoenix entered a Women's team, an "A" team, a second "A" team (the "badgers") and a B team.  The teams were assisted by four drivers who spent the day ferrying the non-runners between each leg.

Some excellent results overall, with a number of runners doing the event for the first time. The women's team ran the distance quicker than they have ever done before, and the "badgers" came second overall. Thanks to Dave Carter and Andy Pumphrey for coming in as very late replacements.

The opening race of the West Sussex Fun Run League is the ever popular Hangover 5M – a  trail run up to Cissbury Ring and back. Bit of a result for family Hoyte we'd say.

Superb run by Reuben Hoyte – race winner in 31:36 with a substantial 21 second lead over the second placed runner. Dad Kurt Hoyte was 15th in a field of 365 runners in a time of 35:28. Phoenix runners both.

As if that wasn't enough, mum Caroline Hoyte running for Arena 80 was first woman home  (14th overall) in 35:26

Sussex Grand Prix kicked off with this popular half marathon - wonderfully supported by the Hastings crowd. Although quite cold fears about the state of the roads were unfounded, with all the snow and ice having melted.  We think we missed out on the team win to the local club Hastings AC.  Tremendous performances all around however, with Paul Whelpton pulling the usual trick of coming quickest not only in his age group but in the one below that.  And within a few seconds of the one below that one too.  It also looks like he now holds the 65+ age group course record. Max Dumbrell made the five-step podium by coming fourth overall. Other prizes will be announced in the near future.
